The Telegraph - Calcutta : Sport

 Sunday, February 06, 2005 

 Raleigh (North Carolina): Kenyan Olympic silver medallist Bernard Lagat streaked to the fastest mile run in Madison Square Garden when he clocked 3:52.87 at the Millrose Games in New York on Friday.

 Lagat?s blistering early pace put him nearly a half a lap ahead of the field and he went on to finish more than seven seconds ahead of countryman Laban Rotich. US Olympian Alan Webb was third. The time broke Algerian Noureddine Morceli?s Madison Square Garden best of 3:52.99 set in 1992. 

 Zurich: Forty Europe-based players, including Thierry Henry, Zinedine Zidane, David Beckham, Paolo Maldini and Patrick Vieira have confirmed to play in a charity soccer match to raise money for tsunami victims.

 All proceeds from the February 15 ?Football for hope? match at the Nou Camp will go to the tsunami solidarity fund set up by Fifa and the Asian Football Confederation.

 Of the 52 players invited, Brazilian stars Ronaldo and Adriano, Italians Roberto Baggio and Francesco Totti and Czech star Pavel Nedved have withdrawn. 

 London: Arsene Wenger has defended his decision not to spend in the transfer market this season and believes Arsenal?s emphasis on youth will reap dividends in the long term. Wenger is adamant he made the right decision to back talent such as teenage midfielder Cesc Fabregas, forward Jose Antonio Reyes and midfielder Matthieu Flamini. He said: ?I feel we have quality but our quality is young. To buy players to put in instead of them I think would be a huge mistake.? 

 Chennai: Five seeded teams, two army squads and Calcuttas Future Hope have made it to the knockout stage of the 7th all-India rugby sevens championship here on Saturday. Future Hope bt Tamil Nadu Police B 27-0.




